article.description:
The Monarchs,who snapped a two-game losing
streak Saturday night with an 80-70 victory over the struggling Sky.
article.headline: Monarchs drop Sky to eighth straight loss
article.linkText: Monarchs drop Sky to eighth straight loss
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Depth and defense were key factors for
the Sacramento Monarchs in winning the WNBA championship last
season.

Although they still have depth, that same defensive intensity
has yet to surface for the Monarchs, who snapped a two-game losing
streak Saturday night with an 80-70 victory over the struggling
Chicago Sky.

Ticha Penicheiro scored 13 points and Yolanda Griffith had 11
points and nine rebounds for Sacramento (4-3), which had eight
players score at least six points. The reserves outscored their
Chicago counterparts 34-9.

"That's what the Monarchs are all about," Penicheiro. "Last
year it (depth) was one of the major reasons we won a championship.
On any given night anyone can have a big game."

No one player had a big game, though plenty contributed as
Sacramento built its lead to nine points by halftime and never
trailed by less than five the remainder of the game.

Candice Dupree and Jia Perkins scored 17 points and had seven
assists for the Sky (1-8), who are winless since an opening-day
victory at Charlotte. Amanda Lassiter had 14 points and Bernadette
Ngoyisa added 11 points and 10 rebounds.

"I think overall we played well," Dupree said. "We tend to
get a little sloppy on offense sometimes and we don't execute our
plays so it makes it difficult to score. They crash the boards hard
and I think that's what probably killed us."

Leading by nine points entering the final period, the Monarchs
went on an 8-0 run to open the fourth and stretch their advantage
to 67-50 with 6:54 remaining.

"We got humbled (in a loss Tuesday) in Phoenix so it was really
good for us to get this win," said Monarchs guard Kara Lawson, who
scored 11 points. "We played well offensively, but we still have a
long way to go on defense."

Reserve Kim Smith scored seven points during a 3-minute stretch
in the first half to help the Monarchs. The rookie made 4 of 5
shots, two of them 3-pointers, and finished with a career-high 10
points in 10 minutes.

"The bench needs to come in and provide a spark and that's what
I tried to do," Smith said. "We have a deep rotation, there is a
likeihood you are probably going to play, and it's just making the
most of your minutes."

The Monarchs were without head coach John Whisenant for the
second straight game following the death of his mother earlier this
week. Whisenant is expected to return for the team's next game, at
Houston on Wednesday.

After getting outplayed early in the game, the Monarchs took
control midway through the second quarter, benefiting from a pair
of 3-pointers by Lawson -- the second to give Sacramento the lead
for good at 31-29.

Lawson and Erin Buescher scored eight points and Kim Smith had
seven in just under 3 minutes of play as the Monarchs led 46-37 at
the half.

"I just thought we got manhandled for a while when they took
over the game," Chicago coach Dave Cowens said. "I thought our
first quarter was excellent. We stepped it up, we made some shots
and we battled, but then we got into a hole."
